        heroSubtitle: "Your Redon → Rennes transfer at €80 — €100. 65 km via the N137.",
        description: "Rennes, capital of Brittany, is 45 minutes from Redon via the toll-free N137 expressway along the Vilaine valley.",
        routeDescription: "The route takes the N137 heading north, a toll-free dual carriageway via Bain-de-Bretagne to the Rennes southern ring road.",
        introduction: "The Redon to Rennes journey links the river town of southern Ille-et-Vilaine to the regional capital of Brittany, following the Vilaine valley, a river that has shaped the landscapes and history of eastern Brittany. Redon, a town of character at the confluence of the Vilaine and the Oust, is an exceptional river crossroads where the Nantes-to-Brest canal meets the navigable Vilaine. Redon's port, once one of the most active in inland Brittany for trading salt, timber and grain, retains its granite quays and warehouses converted into cultural spaces. The Saint-Sauveur Abbey, founded in the 9th century with a Romanesque bell tower featuring four corner turrets unique in Brittany, overlooks the historic heart of the town with its half-timbered houses and medieval lanes. Redon is also an important railway junction: its station, at the crossing of the Rennes-Quimper and Nantes-Brest lines, receives TER services from all four directions. The Nantes-to-Brest canal, a 19th-century engineering masterpiece, runs through the town and offers popular cycling and barge cruising in summer. Rennes, the destination, is a thriving metropolis of 450,000 with exceptional cultural life and an efficient public transport network including its automated metro.",
        itineraire: "From Redon, your driver takes the D177 then the N137, a toll-free dual carriageway forming the main axis between Nantes and Rennes. You leave Redon crossing the Vilaine, a peaceful river winding through the flood meadows of the Redon marshes — a wetland of major ecological importance, home to pike, otters and many migratory birds. The first kilometres follow the Vilaine valley, offering views of the river's meanders bordered by willows and poplars. The road then crosses the rolling countryside of the Redon area, with its bocage hedgerows, cider apple orchards and dairy farms. You pass through Bain-de-Bretagne, a small market town and road junction in southern Ille-et-Vilaine, known for its Friday market. After Bain-de-Bretagne, the N137 widens into a proper divided dual carriageway allowing smooth, fast traffic. The final kilometres cross the suburban communes of the Rennes metropolitan area before joining the southern ring road. The journey takes 45 minutes normally and can reach one hour during Rennes rush hours.",
        conseils: "Before leaving Redon, stroll along the Vilaine and Nantes-to-Brest canal quays — the river port with its locks and colourful barges is picturesque, especially in summer when pleasure craft stop over. The Saint-Sauveur Abbey, with its unique Romanesque bell tower featuring four corner turrets, deserves a quick 15-minute visit. If you visit in October, the Bogue d'Or is an unforgettable festival of Breton music and dance with night-time fest-noz events. In Rennes, do not miss the Lices market on Saturday mornings, the historic quarter from Place des Lices to Rue Saint-Michel and the Parc du Thabor, a magnificent 10-hectare botanical garden. The Musee de Bretagne in the Champs Libres offers a fascinating journey through Breton history and identity.",
        comparaisonTransport: "The TER Redon — Rennes costs about €13 and takes 30 to 45 minutes depending on stops. Frequency is decent: roughly one train per hour on weekdays on the Quimper-Rennes line. The BreizhGo bus also serves this route for about €6. BlaBlaCar offers rides from €5. The TaxiNeo taxi at €80 — €100 provides door-to-door service and full schedule flexibility. For 3-4 passengers, the cost works out to €20-33 per person, very competitive for a direct comfortable transfer, especially with luggage or to reach a specific address in Rennes.",
